    "instruction": "Using the previously computed global P95 thresholds (keep them from kernel memory), filter metric.csv to the incident window 2024-01-20 01:21:01 to 2024-01-20 01:51:01 UTC (inclusive). For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute: total_points_in_window, anomaly_count (value >= global_P95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (UTC datetime) among anomalies, max_value_in_window, global_P95, and severity_ratio = max_value_in_window / global_P95. Only include rows with anomaly_count > 0. Return the top 20 rows sorted by severity_ratio descending. Keep output columns compact and limit rows to 20."
}

{
    "analysis": "The previous step produced anomaly aggregates inside the incident window. Key findings: (1) Several diskio series (catalogue, catalogue-db, rabbitmq) show anomaly_count == total_points_in_window and global_P95 == 0, yielding infinite severity_ratio — this is suspicious and must be validated (possible metric collection quirk, zero-valued historical baseline, or threshold calculation bug). (2) catalogue CPU shows a strong breach (severity ~2.47) with earliest anomaly at 2024-01-20 01:24:00 UTC. (3) queue-master diskio and front-end error/socket/latency also show breaches later in the window. Traces were empty, and logs show no error_count spikes (but front-end and queue-master have high row counts). According to the workflow, we must first verify the global thresholds and raw metric distributions for the top candidates before declaring a root cause. In particular, the diskio global P95==0 cases must be checked by inspecting the full (global) diskio series for catalogue, catalogue-db and rabbitmq to confirm whether the historical values are truly zeros or if aggregation/labeling introduced the zero. We also need to inspect the full global CPU series for catalogue to confirm its elevated values are real and persistent, and to look at the in-window consecutive behavior (fault identification).",
